so the pineal is not the gland
or the organ of sunlight,

00:34:41.990 --> 00:34:43.900
it is the gland of darkness,

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:47.230
in fact, melatonin can be
thought of as a sleepiness signal

00:34:47.230 --> 00:34:48.980
that's correlated with darkness,

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:52.070
so get up each morning,
try and get outside,

00:34:52.070 --> 00:34:53.720
I know that can be challenging for people,

00:34:53.720 --> 00:34:58.120
but anywhere from 2 to 10
minutes of sunlight exposure

00:34:58.120 --> 00:34:59.880
is going to work well for most people,

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:01.740
and you wanna do this on a regular basis

00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:03.620
and you don't have to do
it exactly at sunrise,

00:35:03.620 --> 00:35:05.230
I realize I'm repeating myself,

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:08.360
but somehow, despite
barking at people about this

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:10.000
for a couple years now,

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:11.430
I keep getting the same questions,

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:13.693
and somehow, it hasn't been sinking in,

00:35:14.750 --> 00:35:16.860
which could be related to
some circadian disorder,

00:35:16.860 --> 00:35:18.640
I'm just kidding, if it's not sinking in,

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:20.210
it's probably that I'm not being effective

00:35:20.210 --> 00:35:22.680
in communicating the information,

00:35:22.680 --> 00:35:25.640
but get that bright light
early in the day from sunlight,

00:35:25.640 --> 00:35:26.860
and if you can't get it from sunlight,

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:28.220
get it from artificial light.

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:30.000
What kinds of artificial lights will work?

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:33.150
Well, there are these sunrise simulators,

00:35:33.150 --> 00:35:37.280
but the ring lights that
people use for selfies

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:39.800
and this sort of thing,
for posting on Instagram,

00:35:39.800 --> 00:35:42.100
those generate a lot of blue light.

00:35:42.100 --> 00:35:44.090
If wanna get experimental about this,

00:35:44.090 --> 00:35:46.690
there's a free app, I have
no relationship to the app,

00:35:46.690 --> 00:35:48.840
but it's a great app called Light Meter

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:50.630
that you can use your phone

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:53.070
and you can measure the
amount of photon energy

00:35:53.070 --> 00:35:54.000
in your environment,

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:55.400
and it's kind of a fun experiment to do,

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:56.640
you can go outside in the morning

00:35:56.640 --> 00:35:59.190
and you'll see that
there's 10,000, 20,000 lux,

00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:01.100
even though it might
seem like it's kinda dim

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:02.740
or there's tree cover or cloud cover,

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:06.940
you go inside and you
shine an artificial light

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:07.773
at your phone,

00:36:07.773 --> 00:36:09.150
press the button on Light Meter

00:36:09.150 --> 00:36:11.990
and you'll find that it's
only 500 or 1,000 lux,

00:36:11.990 --> 00:36:15.350
and you realize that even
though it seems really bright,

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:17.890
the artificial light is very condensed,

00:36:17.890 --> 00:36:22.410
whereas the outside light is
scattered in the atmosphere,

00:36:22.410 --> 00:36:24.450
and so you can think that
you're not getting much sunlight

00:36:24.450 --> 00:36:26.080
but you're actually
getting much more outside,

00:36:26.080 --> 00:36:28.300
so get outside, get that
sunlight early in the day,

00:36:28.300 --> 00:36:30.230
and try and do it on a consistent basis.

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:31.410
If you can't do it every day

00:36:31.410 --> 00:36:33.780
or you sleep through this
period of the early day,

00:36:33.780 --> 00:36:34.740
low solar angle,

00:36:34.740 --> 00:36:36.230
don't worry about it,

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:37.610
these systems in the body,

00:36:37.610 --> 00:36:40.140
these hormone systems and
neurotransmitter systems

00:36:40.140 --> 00:36:42.650
that make you awake at
certain periods of the day

00:36:42.650 --> 00:36:44.900
and sleepy at other times

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:47.610
are operating by averaging

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:50.110
when you view the brightest light.

00:36:50.110 --> 00:36:52.900
Now, that can immediately tell us

00:36:52.900 --> 00:36:54.700
that what most people
are doing is terrible,

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:56.550
they're waking up and they're
looking at their phone,

00:36:56.550 --> 00:36:59.320
which isn't triggering activation
of these cells in the eye

00:36:59.320 --> 00:37:01.030
and the central circadian clock,

00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:02.110
then a few hours later,

00:37:02.110 --> 00:37:04.500
they might get in their car
with sunglasses and drive.

00:37:04.500 --> 00:37:07.313
Now, a note about sunglasses
and prescription lenses,

00:37:09.060 --> 00:37:12.340
absolutely never, ever,
ever compromise safety

00:37:12.340 --> 00:37:14.000
for the sorts of things I'm talking about,

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.300
so if you need to wear
sunglasses for safety reasons,

00:37:16.300 --> 00:37:17.340
wear them,

00:37:17.340 --> 00:37:20.190
absolutely, if you wear
prescription lenses or contacts,

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:23.760
wear them, they won't filter
out the wavelengths of light

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:26.130
that are necessary for
setting these central clocks,

00:37:26.130 --> 00:37:28.200
so safety first, of course,

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:30.470
if you have a retinal
degenerative disorder,

00:37:30.470 --> 00:37:33.360
retinitis pigmentosa, macular
degeneration, or glaucoma,

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:35.410
or those run in your family,

00:37:35.410 --> 00:37:38.700
you want to avoid excessively
bright light all the time,

00:37:38.700 --> 00:37:40.340
you wanna be very cautious about that,

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:43.060
you're going to wanna
get your light exposure

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:46.810
through seeing dimmer
light, including sunlight,

00:37:46.810 --> 00:37:48.810
but for longer periods of time, perhaps.

00:37:49.700 --> 00:37:51.207
You might immediately ask,

00:37:51.207 --> 00:37:53.757
"What about low-vision or blind people,

00:37:53.757 --> 00:37:55.380
"how do they set these central clocks?"

00:37:55.380 --> 00:37:58.030
Well, turns out that
low-vision and blind people,

00:37:58.030 --> 00:38:00.300
most of them, provided
they still have eyes,

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:01.300
that the eyes weren't removed

00:38:01.300 --> 00:38:03.720
because of a burn or a tumor
or something like that,

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:07.800
still maintain these neurons
that set the circadian clock,

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:10.310
which brings me to a
really important point,

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:13.760
it's not about seeing
and perceiving the sun,

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:17.620
this is a subconscious mechanism
by which these neurons,

00:38:17.620 --> 00:38:20.900
which are called
melanopsin ganglion cells,

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:24.620
these neurons set your central clocks

00:38:24.620 --> 00:38:28.090
by getting activated by the
particular wavelengths of light

00:38:28.090 --> 00:38:29.570
that are present in the atmosphere,

00:38:29.570 --> 00:38:31.223
even coming through cloud cover,

00:38:32.060 --> 00:38:35.210
and you don't need to
see or perceive the sun

00:38:35.210 --> 00:38:37.610
in order to get this mechanism to start.

00:38:37.610 --> 00:38:39.560
Now, it's such a vitally
important mechanism

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:42.910
because it dictates how well

00:38:42.910 --> 00:38:46.310
and what time you will want to
fall asleep later in the day,

00:38:46.310 --> 00:38:47.900
so for those of you that are night owls

00:38:47.900 --> 00:38:49.157
and you insist that you're a night owl

00:38:49.157 --> 00:38:51.110
and you have the genetic polymorphism

00:38:51.110 --> 00:38:52.110
that makes you a night owl,

00:38:52.110 --> 00:38:54.850
you may very well have
that genetic polymorphism,

00:38:54.850 --> 00:38:56.930
those genes that make
you want to stay up late

00:38:56.930 --> 00:38:58.710
and wake up late,

00:38:58.710 --> 00:39:00.400
but chances are, about half of you

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:01.960
that think that you're night owls

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:04.880
are just not getting enough
sunlight early in the day.

00:39:04.880 --> 00:39:08.410
So viewing light early in
the day, ideally sunlight,

00:39:08.410 --> 00:39:12.530
is key for establishing
healthy sleep-wake rhythms

00:39:12.530 --> 00:39:16.460
and for allowing you to
fall asleep easily at night.

00:39:16.460 --> 00:39:17.780
Now, it's not gonna make sure

00:39:17.780 --> 00:39:19.690
that all that happens every single time,

00:39:19.690 --> 00:39:23.057
but it is the foundation of proper sleep

00:39:23.057 --> 00:39:25.460
and what we call circadian health,

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:28.640
it governs metabolism
and so many other things

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:32.223
that are supposed to exist
on a regular 24-hour cycle.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:36.087
Some of you, many of you, might be asking,

00:39:36.087 --> 00:39:37.980
"What else can help set this rhythm?"

00:39:37.980 --> 00:39:39.520
Well, it turns out that light

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:43.990
is what we call the primary
zeitgeber, the time giver,

00:39:43.990 --> 00:39:48.930
but other things can help
establish this rhythm of cortisol

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:52.520
followed by melatonin 12
to 16 hours later as well.

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:54.480
The other things besides light

00:39:54.480 --> 00:39:58.960
are timing of food intake,
timing of exercise,

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:03.410
as well as various drugs or
chemicals that one might ingest,

00:40:03.410 --> 00:40:04.490
not illegal drugs,

00:40:04.490 --> 00:40:07.333
although those will impact
circadian mechanisms as well,

00:40:08.240 --> 00:40:10.560
but the reason we focus
so heavily on light

00:40:10.560 --> 00:40:15.560
is that light is the main
way that this central clock,

00:40:15.730 --> 00:40:18.677
the suprachiasmatic nucleus,
was supposed to be set,

00:40:18.677 --> 00:40:22.380
and we know that because
it's the only direct input

00:40:22.380 --> 00:40:23.480
to the clock.

00:40:23.480 --> 00:40:25.590
These neurons in the eye that
are also part of the brain

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:27.760
that we call melanopsin ganglion cells

00:40:27.760 --> 00:40:30.290
that, not so incidentally, were discovered

00:40:30.290 --> 00:40:33.800
by my friend and colleague David
Berson at Brown University,

00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:37.380
and others, Samer Hattar,
King-Wai Yau, et cetera,

00:40:37.380 --> 00:40:39.530
worked out the mechanisms,
the molecular mechanisms,

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:41.560
but it was really David Berson

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:45.363
that discovered these
incredibly fascinating,

00:40:46.270 --> 00:40:48.570
you know, these are cells that
aren't important for sight

00:40:48.570 --> 00:40:49.500
like pattern vision,

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:51.980
but are for setting our clocks,

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:55.090
David's really credited
with making that discovery.

00:40:55.090 --> 00:40:58.640
Those cells are the main way

00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:01.500
and the only direct way to set the clock,

00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:03.070
in fact, it's fair to say

00:41:03.070 --> 00:41:06.700
that light viewed by
these melanopsin cells,

00:41:06.700 --> 00:41:08.630
in particular, sunlight,

00:41:08.630 --> 00:41:12.500
is 1,000 to 10,000 times more effective

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:16.070
than, say, getting up in
darkness and just exercising.

00:41:16.070 --> 00:41:17.110
That doesn't mean that you shouldn't

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:18.800
exercise early in the day in darkness

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:20.070
if that's what you like to do,

00:41:20.070 --> 00:41:22.370
it will have somewhat an effect

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:25.130
on raising your wakefulness
early in the day

00:41:25.130 --> 00:41:27.620
and setting these rhythms,

00:41:27.620 --> 00:41:29.500
and this is because of
some other pathways,

00:41:29.500 --> 00:41:30.820
for the aficionados out there

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:33.090
who wanna know more neuroscience,

00:41:33.090 --> 00:41:35.030
here's how it goes, you've got this clock

00:41:35.030 --> 00:41:35.930
above the roof of your mouth

00:41:35.930 --> 00:41:37.720
that churns out this 24-hour rhythm

00:41:37.720 --> 00:41:39.630
and it's communicated
to all the other organs

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:41.160
and tissues of your body,

00:41:41.160 --> 00:41:42.550
but there's another structure,

00:41:42.550 --> 00:41:45.870
it has a cool name, it's called
the intergeniculate leaflet,

00:41:45.870 --> 00:41:48.350
which sits a few millimeters
away in the brain,

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:51.580
and it's involved in
regulating the clock output

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:55.680
through what's called non-photic,
non-light-type influences

00:41:55.680 --> 00:41:58.470
like exercise and feeding, et cetera.

00:41:58.470 --> 00:42:02.420
So if you are not feeling
awake during the day

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:04.210
and you're having trouble sleeping,

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:07.170
get the sunlight exposure
that we just talked about,

00:42:07.170 --> 00:42:09.180
but in addition to that,

00:42:09.180 --> 00:42:11.540
if you wanna become an
early riser, for instance,

00:42:11.540 --> 00:42:12.660
and you wanna feel more awake

00:42:12.660 --> 00:42:15.200
during the early part of the day,

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:16.500
by getting that light exposure

00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:19.000
and exercising early in the day,

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.250
you will, after two or three days,

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:23.690
you will naturally start to
wake up earlier in the day,

00:42:23.690 --> 00:42:26.130
and that's because these
clock mechanisms have shifted,

00:42:26.130 --> 00:42:27.860
it's like setting the clock earlier

00:42:27.860 --> 00:42:30.280
as opposed to delaying the clock,

00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:33.530
and that takes us to a
somewhat complicated,

00:42:33.530 --> 00:42:35.810
but very important, aspect to all this,

00:42:35.810 --> 00:42:39.400
which is, what sets the
clock and keeps it anchored?

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:42.570
The main thing is that bright
light early in the day,

00:42:42.570 --> 00:42:44.500
the other thing is sunset,

00:42:44.500 --> 00:42:47.680
when the sun is also at low solar angle,

00:42:47.680 --> 00:42:49.333
low, close to the horizon,

00:42:50.290 --> 00:42:53.520
by viewing sunlight at that
time of day in the evening,

00:42:53.520 --> 00:42:55.410
or afternoon, depending
on what time of year it is

00:42:55.410 --> 00:42:57.340
and where you are in the world,

00:42:57.340 --> 00:42:59.800
these melanopsin cells,
these neurons in your eye,

00:42:59.800 --> 00:43:01.970
signal the central circadian clock

00:43:01.970 --> 00:43:04.090
that it's the end of the day,

00:43:04.090 --> 00:43:05.510
and there's a really nice study

00:43:05.510 --> 00:43:06.940
that was published last year,

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:09.770
and I will put links to
these references on a website

00:43:09.770 --> 00:43:11.860
not too long from now,

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:14.780
there was a really nice study that showed

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:18.910
that viewing sunlight around
the time of the sunset,

00:43:18.910 --> 00:43:21.320
doesn't have to be just
crossing the horizon,

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:23.470
but circa sunset,

00:43:23.470 --> 00:43:25.273
within an hour or so of sunset,

00:43:26.470 --> 00:43:29.930
prevents some of the bad effects of light

00:43:29.930 --> 00:43:33.860
in preventing melatonin
release later that same night,

00:43:33.860 --> 00:43:34.800
so let me repeat this,

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:36.330
viewing light early in the day is key,

00:43:36.330 --> 00:43:38.260
viewing light later in the day

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:41.270
when the sun is setting,
or around that time,

00:43:41.270 --> 00:43:45.290
can help protect these
mechanisms, your brain and body,

00:43:45.290 --> 00:43:48.820
against the negative effects
of light later in the day,

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:51.290
so let me talk about you would do that,

00:43:51.290 --> 00:43:52.650
you'd go view the sunset

00:43:52.650 --> 00:43:55.920
or you would go outside in
the late afternoon or evening,

00:43:55.920 --> 00:43:57.410
again, if you safely can do that

00:43:57.410 --> 00:43:59.410
with sunglasses off, you will,

00:43:59.410 --> 00:44:00.650
if you need to wear sunglasses, fine,

00:44:00.650 --> 00:44:03.810
but it will take probably
100 to 1,000 times longer

00:44:03.810 --> 00:44:06.160
with dark sunglasses than
if you take them off,

00:44:07.810 --> 00:44:09.680
again, if you wanna do this
through a window at work,

00:44:09.680 --> 00:44:12.080
that's fine, but it'll
take 50 times longer,

00:44:12.080 --> 00:44:13.040
so the best thing to do is

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:15.020
just to get outside for a few minutes,

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:17.780
anywhere from 2 to 10 minutes,
also in the afternoon.

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:21.140
Having those two signals
arriving to your central clock

00:44:21.140 --> 00:44:23.560
that your body, your internal world,

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:25.770
knows when it's morning and
knows when it's evening,

00:44:25.770 --> 00:44:28.020
is tremendously powerful.

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:30.030
Maybe think about it this way,

00:44:30.030 --> 00:44:33.090
every cell in your body
needs glucose and energy,

00:44:33.090 --> 00:44:35.230
it needs, whether or not
it gets that from meats

00:44:35.230 --> 00:44:37.760
or it gets it from ketones or
it gets it from carbohydrates

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:39.510
or fruit or vegetables, it doesn't matter,

