extraocular photo reception in humans.

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:04.690
Whatever somebody tells you

00:46:04.690 --> 00:46:07.470
that light to the skin
or light to the wherever

00:46:07.470 --> 00:46:09.500
is beneficial for your health,

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:10.700
we can talk about that,

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:12.760
but there's no way that light information

00:46:12.760 --> 00:46:14.720
is setting your clocks,

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:16.930
you need these cells in your eyes

00:46:16.930 --> 00:46:19.740
to perceive or to see light

00:46:19.740 --> 00:46:22.060
at the particular times of
day that I'm referring to.

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:25.100
Some animals, like snakes
and other reptiles,

00:46:25.100 --> 00:46:27.760
actually have a hole in
the top of their skull

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:30.510
to get light information
directly to their pineal

00:46:31.350 --> 00:46:32.940
to suppress melatonin.

00:46:32.940 --> 00:46:34.000
We don't have that hole,

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.160
I mean, most of you don't
have holes in your skull.

00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:38.720
These holes in your skull

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:41.340
that we call the sockets for the eyes

00:46:41.340 --> 00:46:45.380
are actually there primarily
to allow light information

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:46.650
to this central clock,

00:46:46.650 --> 00:46:48.710
and then vision and pattern
vision and color vision

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:50.580
came much later in evolution,

00:46:50.580 --> 00:46:52.360
we know this on the
basis of genetic studies

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:55.120
we get to discuss in a future podcast.

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:56.930
So get that light information

00:46:56.930 --> 00:46:59.060
to the cells of your brain and body

00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:01.450
by viewing sunlight at
the two times of day

00:47:01.450 --> 00:47:02.433
that I referred to.

00:47:04.020 --> 00:47:05.617
There's always a lot of questions about,

00:47:05.617 --> 00:47:07.880
"How long, how much, how do
I know if I've had enough?"

00:47:07.880 --> 00:47:09.900
You'll know because your rhythm

00:47:09.900 --> 00:47:13.200
will start to fall into
some degree of normalcy,

00:47:13.200 --> 00:47:14.080
you'll start to wake up

00:47:14.080 --> 00:47:15.710
at more or less the same time each day,

00:47:15.710 --> 00:47:17.370
you'll fall asleep more easily at night,

00:47:17.370 --> 00:47:19.070
generally, it takes
about two or three days

00:47:19.070 --> 00:47:20.760
for these systems to align,

00:47:20.760 --> 00:47:22.990
so if you've not been
doing these behaviors,

00:47:22.990 --> 00:47:24.230
it's gonna take a few days,

00:47:24.230 --> 00:47:26.330
but they can have tremendous benefits,

00:47:26.330 --> 00:47:27.550
and sometimes rather quickly,

00:47:27.550 --> 00:47:30.320
on a number of different
mental and physical aspects

00:47:30.320 --> 00:47:31.153
of your health.

00:47:32.990 --> 00:47:35.830
Now let's talk about
the bad effects of light

00:47:35.830 --> 00:47:40.340
because light is not supposed
to arrive in our system

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:41.560
at any time,

00:47:41.560 --> 00:47:44.490
and nowadays, because of
screens and artificial light,

00:47:44.490 --> 00:47:48.580
we have access to light
at times of day and night

00:47:48.580 --> 00:47:50.610
that normally we wouldn't.

00:47:50.610 --> 00:47:53.290
Now, earlier I said that
you need a lot of light,

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:54.123
in particular, sunlight,

00:47:54.123 --> 00:47:56.290
to set these clock mechanisms,

00:47:56.290 --> 00:47:59.110
that's true, but there's a
kind of diabolical feature

00:47:59.110 --> 00:48:00.230
to the way all of this works,

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:02.943
which is the longer you've been awake,

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:08.070
the more sensitive your retina
and these cells are to light,

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:11.830
so that if you've been
awake for 10, 12, 14 hours,

00:48:11.830 --> 00:48:14.760
it becomes very easy for
even a small amount of light

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:19.490
coming from a screen or
from an overhead light

00:48:19.490 --> 00:48:21.800
to trigger the activation of the clock

00:48:21.800 --> 00:48:23.660
and make you feel like
you wanna stay up later,

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:24.920
make it harder to fall asleep,

00:48:24.920 --> 00:48:27.350
and disrupt your sleep pattern, okay?

00:48:27.350 --> 00:48:29.620
So the simple way to think about this is

00:48:29.620 --> 00:48:32.280
you want as much light
as is safely possible

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:34.640
early in the day, morning
and throughout the day,

00:48:34.640 --> 00:48:35.840
including blue light,

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:37.860
so take those blue
blockers off during the day

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:40.870
unless you have a real issue
with screen light sensitivity,

00:48:40.870 --> 00:48:43.860
and you want as little
light coming into your eyes,

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:45.920
artificial or sunlight,

00:48:45.920 --> 00:48:47.610
after, say, 8:00 p.m.,

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:49.690
and certainly, you do not want to get

00:48:49.690 --> 00:48:50.980
bright light exposure to your eyes

00:48:50.980 --> 00:48:54.080
between 11:00 p.m. and
4:00 a.m., and here's why,

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:56.160
David Berson, who I mentioned before,

00:48:56.160 --> 00:48:58.320
and another and friend and
colleague, Samer Hattar,

00:48:58.320 --> 00:49:00.050
who's director of the chronobiology unit

00:49:00.050 --> 00:49:02.240
at the National Institutes
of Mental Health

00:49:02.240 --> 00:49:05.790
published a paper in
"Cell," which is a journal,

00:49:05.790 --> 00:49:07.950
another excellent journal,
very high stringency,

00:49:07.950 --> 00:49:12.950
showing that light that
arrives to the eyes

00:49:13.060 --> 00:49:16.880
between 11:00 p.m. and
4:00 a.m., approximately,

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:20.340
suppresses the release of dopamine,

00:49:20.340 --> 00:49:22.250
this neuromodulator
that makes us feel good,

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:24.550
and it's sort of an
endogenous antidepressant,

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:27.040
and can inhibit learning

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:30.630
and create all sorts of
other detrimental effects,

00:49:30.630 --> 00:49:32.310
it does this through a mechanism,

00:49:32.310 --> 00:49:34.480
for those of you that wanna
know the neural pathways,

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:35.900
that involves light to the eyes

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.856
that's then signaled to a
structure called the habenula,

00:49:38.856 --> 00:49:40.640
the habenula looks like
two little bat ears

00:49:40.640 --> 00:49:42.530
sitting right in the middle
of a structure in your brain

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:43.550
called the thalamus,

00:49:43.550 --> 00:49:44.650
don't worry about these names

00:49:44.650 --> 00:49:45.720
if you're not interested in this stuff,

00:49:45.720 --> 00:49:48.440
if you are, these are
just avenues to explore,

00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:50.360
when that habenula gets activated

00:49:50.360 --> 00:49:53.130
it's actually called the
disappointment nucleus

00:49:53.130 --> 00:49:57.090
because it actually
makes us feel less happy

00:49:57.090 --> 00:49:58.190
and more disappointed,

00:49:58.190 --> 00:50:00.700
and can lead to certain
forms of depression

00:50:00.700 --> 00:50:02.180
in the wakeful state.

00:50:02.180 --> 00:50:03.460
Now, if you wake up in
the middle of the night

00:50:03.460 --> 00:50:04.460
and you need to use the bathroom

00:50:04.460 --> 00:50:05.770
or you're on an all-night flight

00:50:05.770 --> 00:50:10.323
and you're, you know, need to
read or whatever it is, fine,

00:50:11.380 --> 00:50:13.340
every once in a while,
it's not gonna be a problem

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:15.420
to get bright light exposure to your eyes

00:50:15.420 --> 00:50:16.860
in the middle of the night,

00:50:16.860 --> 00:50:19.530
but if you think about
our lifestyle nowadays

00:50:19.530 --> 00:50:21.140
and being up late looking at phones,

00:50:21.140 --> 00:50:22.820
even if you dim that screen,

00:50:22.820 --> 00:50:24.700
you're triggering this activation

00:50:24.700 --> 00:50:26.160
because your retinal sensitivity

00:50:26.160 --> 00:50:28.310
and the sensitivity of
these neurons has gone up

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:29.720
late in the day.

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:30.750
Now, I'm not here to dictate

00:50:30.750 --> 00:50:32.080
what you should or shouldn't do,

00:50:32.080 --> 00:50:33.080
but for those of you that are

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:35.300
experiencing challenges with mood,

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:36.580
those of you that have anxiety,

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:39.210
learning problems, issues focusing,

00:50:39.210 --> 00:50:41.350
the questions I usually get
are, "How can I focus better?"

00:50:41.350 --> 00:50:43.080
Well, we will get to that,

00:50:43.080 --> 00:50:45.340
but one of the best ways you can support

00:50:45.340 --> 00:50:47.980
your mechanisms for good
mood, mental health,

00:50:47.980 --> 00:50:50.800
learning, focus, metabolism, et cetera,

00:50:50.800 --> 00:50:55.670
is to take control of this
light exposure behavior at night

00:50:55.670 --> 00:50:58.780
and not get much or any
bright light exposure

00:50:58.780 --> 00:50:59.950
in the middle of the night.

00:50:59.950 --> 00:51:02.610
Red light won't trigger this pathway,

00:51:02.610 --> 00:51:05.230
but very few people have
the kind of infrared lights

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:06.957
that are set up, or floor lights,

00:51:06.957 --> 00:51:09.170
and that brings me to an important point,

00:51:09.170 --> 00:51:10.690
which is about the location of light,

00:51:10.690 --> 00:51:13.600
this hasn't been discussed
much out there, I don't think,

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:15.410
these cells in our eye,

00:51:15.410 --> 00:51:18.250
these neurons that
signal the central clock,

00:51:18.250 --> 00:51:21.100
reside mostly, not
exclusively, but mostly,

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:23.180
in the bottom half of our retina,

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:25.800
and because we have a lens
in front of our retina,

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:27.870
and because of the optics of lenses,

00:51:27.870 --> 00:51:29.630
that means that these cells

00:51:29.630 --> 00:51:32.000
are actually viewing
our upper visual field,

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.520
there's an inversion of the
visual image, et cetera,

00:51:34.520 --> 00:51:36.170
you can look that up
if you wanna learn more

00:51:36.170 --> 00:51:38.510
about retinal optics, it's fascinating,

00:51:38.510 --> 00:51:40.620
but not the topic for today.

00:51:40.620 --> 00:51:42.950
These cells are in the bottom
half of your retina mostly,

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:47.950
and so they're viewing the
overhead visual space around you.

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:52.440
This is probably not
coincidental that these cells

00:51:52.440 --> 00:51:55.970
were essentially designed
to detect sunlight,

00:51:55.970 --> 00:51:58.120
which is overhead, of course,

00:51:58.120 --> 00:52:01.630
so if you want to avoid

00:52:01.630 --> 00:52:05.660
improper activation of these neurons,

00:52:05.660 --> 00:52:08.970
it's better to place lights
that you use in the evening

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:10.830
low in your physical environment,

00:52:10.830 --> 00:52:15.640
so on desktops or even the
floor, if you wanna go that way,

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:17.980
as opposed to overhead lights,

00:52:17.980 --> 00:52:20.950
so overhead florescent
lights would be the worst,

00:52:20.950 --> 00:52:23.340
that would be the worst case scenario,

00:52:23.340 --> 00:52:25.790
lights that are overhead
that are a little bit softer,

00:52:25.790 --> 00:52:28.040
of the sort or yellow or reddish tints,

00:52:28.040 --> 00:52:29.090
would be slightly better,

00:52:29.090 --> 00:52:31.710
but dim lights that
are set low in the room

00:52:31.710 --> 00:52:32.730
are going to be best

00:52:32.730 --> 00:52:36.230
because they aren't going
to activate these neurons

00:52:36.230 --> 00:52:39.160
and therefore shift your circadian clock,

00:52:39.160 --> 00:52:40.570
so that's a goal.

00:52:40.570 --> 00:52:43.610
Some people, like Samer Hattar
that I mentioned earlier,

00:52:43.610 --> 00:52:46.700
he turns his home basically
into a cave in the evenings.

00:52:46.700 --> 00:52:49.120
Candlelight actually does not

00:52:49.120 --> 00:52:50.690
trigger activation of these cells,

00:52:50.690 --> 00:52:55.690
so candlelight and fireplaces
and campfires are fine,

00:52:56.320 --> 00:52:58.300
dim lights, very dim lights are fine,

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:00.050
and lights low in the
physical environment,

00:53:00.050 --> 00:53:02.720
of course, the problem with
candlelight and fireplaces

00:53:02.720 --> 00:53:03.650
is the fire hazard,

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:06.713
but you're smart people, you
know what to do about that.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:10.850
Don't burn down whatever
structure you're in,

00:53:10.850 --> 00:53:13.260
including forests, please.

00:53:13.260 --> 00:53:16.880
So, keep the lights low
in in your environment.

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:19.010
What if you wake up in
the middle of the night

00:53:19.010 --> 00:53:22.733
and you find yourself watching
TV or on the computer?

00:53:23.731 --> 00:53:25.800
Well, in that case, you might
wanna wear blue blockers,

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:28.110
and you certainly would
wanna dim the screen,

00:53:28.110 --> 00:53:29.630
but ideally, you're not doing that,

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:32.660
it's remarkable the positive effects

00:53:32.660 --> 00:53:34.630
of getting that bit of
sunlight early in the day,

00:53:34.630 --> 00:53:36.220
maybe even also around sunset,

00:53:36.220 --> 00:53:38.090
and avoiding bright lights,

00:53:38.090 --> 00:53:40.560
and especially overhead bright lights,

00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:42.730
between about 11:00 p.m. and 4:00 a.m..

00:53:42.730 --> 00:53:44.470
Now, I'm not talking about shift work,

00:53:44.470 --> 00:53:46.070
I'm realizing that we're probably

