and I don't wanna
complicate this too much,

00:57:07.190 --> 00:57:09.640
so the simplest way to think about

00:57:09.640 --> 00:57:12.090
phase advances and phase delays

00:57:12.090 --> 00:57:15.337
is that if you see light late in the day,

00:57:15.337 --> 00:57:17.910
and in particular, in
the middle of the night,

00:57:17.910 --> 00:57:22.340
your brain and body, for
reasons that now you understand,

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.430
will think that that's morning light

00:57:24.430 --> 00:57:25.570
even though it's not sunlight

00:57:25.570 --> 00:57:27.150
because you have this
heightened sensitivity,

00:57:27.150 --> 00:57:29.910
and it will phase delay,
it will delay your clock,

00:57:29.910 --> 00:57:32.050
it will essentially make
you want to get up later

00:57:32.050 --> 00:57:33.780
and go to sleep later,

00:57:33.780 --> 00:57:36.550
so if you get light exposure
too late in the evening

00:57:36.550 --> 00:57:37.940
or in the middle of the night,

00:57:37.940 --> 00:57:39.280
it's going to make it hard

00:57:39.280 --> 00:57:41.540
to want to wake up that next morning early

00:57:41.540 --> 00:57:42.843
and to go to bed early.

00:57:44.370 --> 00:57:49.370
The opposite is also true,
if you wake up early,

00:57:49.650 --> 00:57:54.340
say, 6:00 a.m. or 7:00 a.m.,
and get light exposure,

00:57:54.340 --> 00:57:57.300
or even earlier, 4:00 a.m.,
and get light exposure,

00:57:57.300 --> 00:58:00.100
it will phase-advance your clock, okay?

00:58:00.100 --> 00:58:02.620
It's gonna make your
clock think it's earlier

00:58:02.620 --> 00:58:04.400
and you'll wanna wake up earlier,

00:58:04.400 --> 00:58:06.730
so the simple way to think about this

00:58:06.730 --> 00:58:08.870
is if you're having
trouble waking up early

00:58:08.870 --> 00:58:11.690
and feeling alert early in the day,

00:58:11.690 --> 00:58:14.300
you're going to wanna try
and get bright light exposure

00:58:14.300 --> 00:58:18.070
even before waking up because
it will advance your clock,

00:58:18.070 --> 00:58:20.220
it's sort of like turning
the clock forward,

00:58:20.220 --> 00:58:22.730
whereas if you are having
trouble waking up early,

00:58:22.730 --> 00:58:24.860
you definitely don't want to get

00:58:24.860 --> 00:58:27.110
too much light exposure
or any light exposure

00:58:27.110 --> 00:58:29.410
to your eyes late in the evening

00:58:29.410 --> 00:58:30.260
and in the middle of the night

00:58:30.260 --> 00:58:33.160
because it's just gonna delay
your clock more and more,

00:58:33.160 --> 00:58:35.460
so rather than get into the specifics

00:58:35.460 --> 00:58:36.720
of everybody's situation

00:58:36.720 --> 00:58:38.070
because there are many of you out there

00:58:38.070 --> 00:58:39.220
with different situations

00:58:39.220 --> 00:58:42.390
and lifestyle requirements, et cetera,

00:58:42.390 --> 00:58:44.000
the way to think about this

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:46.270
is that you have these internal mechanisms

00:58:46.270 --> 00:58:47.990
of adenosine and circadian clocks,

00:58:47.990 --> 00:58:49.600
and they're always operating,

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:52.450
and what you're trying to
do is provide them anchors,

00:58:52.450 --> 00:58:55.910
you're trying to provide them
consistent, powerful anchors

00:58:55.910 --> 00:58:59.280
so that your cortisol, your melatonin,

00:58:59.280 --> 00:59:02.450
and then everything that
cascades down from that,

00:59:02.450 --> 00:59:05.170
like your metabolism and
your ability to learn

00:59:05.170 --> 00:59:08.260
and your sense of alertness,
your dopamine, your serotonin,

00:59:08.260 --> 00:59:11.620
all that stuff is timed regularly,

00:59:11.620 --> 00:59:16.620
one of the reasons why there's
so much challenge out there

00:59:16.880 --> 00:59:20.000
with focus and anxiety and depression,

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:21.310
there are a lot of reasons for that,

00:59:21.310 --> 00:59:25.420
but one of the reasons is that
people's internal mechanisms

00:59:25.420 --> 00:59:27.680
aren't anchored to anything regular.

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:30.670
Now, this doesn't require
being neurotically attached

00:59:30.670 --> 00:59:33.180
to getting up at a very
specific time, going outside,

00:59:33.180 --> 00:59:35.270
viewing the sunlight at
the same time every day,

00:59:35.270 --> 00:59:36.810
these systems, again, will average,

00:59:36.810 --> 00:59:39.910
but if you can provide them
consistent light anchors

00:59:39.910 --> 00:59:41.790
early in the day and in the evening,

00:59:41.790 --> 00:59:43.370
and avoiding light at night,

00:59:43.370 --> 00:59:45.740
you will be amazed at
the tremendous number

00:59:45.740 --> 00:59:48.030
of positive effects
that can come from that

00:59:48.030 --> 00:59:51.000
at the level of metabolic
factors, hormones,

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:53.460
and just general feelings of wellbeing,

00:59:53.460 --> 00:59:56.330
in fact, most of us are familiar

00:59:56.330 --> 00:59:58.380
with what it is to not sleep well

00:59:58.380 --> 01:00:00.000
and all the terrible effects that has,

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.370
maybe one night you're
fine, two nights even,

01:00:02.370 --> 01:00:06.150
for the new parents out
there, I sympathize with you,

01:00:06.150 --> 01:00:09.570
but most people are not
familiar with what it is

01:00:09.570 --> 01:00:13.420
to sleep really, really
well on a consistent basis,

01:00:13.420 --> 01:00:15.180
and when you start doing that

01:00:15.180 --> 01:00:17.040
by controlling your
sleep environment, right,

01:00:17.040 --> 01:00:19.830
get the proper sleep surface,
get the proper pillow,

01:00:19.830 --> 01:00:21.840
get the temperature in the room right,

01:00:21.840 --> 01:00:23.800
get your light exposure right,

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:26.750
start timing your exercise
at normal periods or times

01:00:26.750 --> 01:00:28.820
throughout the day and week,

01:00:28.820 --> 01:00:31.370
it's amazing how many
other biological systems

01:00:31.370 --> 01:00:33.120
just naturally fall in line,

01:00:33.120 --> 01:00:35.847
and this is why whenever people ask me,

01:00:35.847 --> 01:00:36.800
"What should I take?"

01:00:36.800 --> 01:00:38.427
which is one of the most
common questions I get,

01:00:38.427 --> 01:00:39.477
"What supplement should I take?

01:00:39.477 --> 01:00:40.647
"What drug should I be taking?

01:00:40.647 --> 01:00:42.320
"What things should I be taking?"

01:00:42.320 --> 01:00:47.320
The first question I always ask
them is, "How's your sleep?"

01:00:47.520 --> 01:00:49.610
and 90% of the time, they tell me

01:00:49.610 --> 01:00:51.810
they either have trouble
falling asleep or staying asleep

01:00:51.810 --> 01:00:54.420
or they don't feel rested
throughout the day.

01:00:54.420 --> 01:00:56.640
A brief note about naps,

01:00:56.640 --> 01:00:59.640
naps, provided that they're
less than one ultradian cycle,

01:00:59.640 --> 01:01:02.580
provided they're 20 minutes
or 30 minutes or even an hour,

01:01:02.580 --> 01:01:04.650
can be very beneficial
for a lot of people,

01:01:04.650 --> 01:01:06.290
you don't have to take them,

01:01:06.290 --> 01:01:08.580
but many people naturally feel a dip

01:01:08.580 --> 01:01:10.660
in energy and focus late in the afternoon,

01:01:10.660 --> 01:01:12.800
in fact, if we were gonna
look at wakefulness,

01:01:12.800 --> 01:01:14.040
what we would find is that you get

01:01:14.040 --> 01:01:15.480
that morning light exposure, hopefully,

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:17.550
your cortisol goes up, people
will start feeling awake,

01:01:17.550 --> 01:01:19.880
and then around two, or three,
or four in the afternoon,

01:01:19.880 --> 01:01:22.400
there's a spike in everything

01:01:22.400 --> 01:01:24.890
from alertness to ability to learn,

01:01:24.890 --> 01:01:26.460
some metabolic factors drop,

01:01:26.460 --> 01:01:28.590
and then it just naturally comes back up,

01:01:28.590 --> 01:01:31.240
and then it tapers off
as the night goes on.

01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:33.760
So for some of you, naps are great,

01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:35.350
I love taking naps,

01:01:35.350 --> 01:01:38.450
some people, they wake up from
naps feeling really groggy,

01:01:38.450 --> 01:01:40.350
that's probably because
they're not sleeping

01:01:40.350 --> 01:01:42.540
as well as they should at night

01:01:42.540 --> 01:01:43.740
or as long as they should at night,

01:01:43.740 --> 01:01:46.380
and so they're dropping into REM sleep

01:01:46.380 --> 01:01:49.060
or deeper forms of sleep in the day time,

01:01:49.060 --> 01:01:51.290
and then they wake up and
they feel kind of disoriented,

01:01:51.290 --> 01:01:52.900
other people feel great after a nap,

01:01:52.900 --> 01:01:55.360
so that's another case where,
just like with caffeine,

01:01:55.360 --> 01:01:58.010
so sort of have to evaluate for yourself.

01:01:58.010 --> 01:01:59.610
As we discuss this,
you're probably realizing

01:01:59.610 --> 01:02:02.700
this is a lot like nutrition
where nowadays it's just crazy,

01:02:02.700 --> 01:02:04.240
I mean, if you go on social media,

01:02:04.240 --> 01:02:06.370
it's like you've got people
who are pushing carnivore,

01:02:06.370 --> 01:02:08.310
you've got other people
who are pushing vegan,

01:02:08.310 --> 01:02:11.070
other people who are pushing paleo,

01:02:11.070 --> 01:02:13.030
every variation of every diet,

01:02:13.030 --> 01:02:14.910
and there's a lot of data to support

01:02:14.910 --> 01:02:17.340
any and all of those and
the arguments go on and on,

01:02:17.340 --> 01:02:19.500
and there's probably a
lot of genetic variation

01:02:19.500 --> 01:02:21.000
and lifestyle variation

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:22.410
that's going to dictate whether or not

01:02:22.410 --> 01:02:24.270
something is good for you,
whether or not you like it,

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:26.050
whether or not you'll stick to it.

01:02:26.050 --> 01:02:29.840
The same thing is true for circadian

01:02:29.840 --> 01:02:32.680
and sleep and wakefulness behaviors,

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:34.390
except the light-viewing behavior

01:02:34.390 --> 01:02:36.370
that I talked about before,
there's no way around that,

01:02:36.370 --> 01:02:37.870
that's hardwired into our system,

01:02:37.870 --> 01:02:41.230
the same way we could factually say

01:02:41.230 --> 01:02:43.760
that everybody needs some nutrition

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:45.580
at some level from some source,

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:47.500
everybody needs light information

01:02:47.500 --> 01:02:51.700
arriving in their system in
some way at regular intervals,

01:02:51.700 --> 01:02:54.080
so that's really what this is about.

01:02:54.080 --> 01:02:56.000
Okay, so naps are gonna
be good for some people,

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:56.833
not for others,

01:02:56.833 --> 01:02:59.280
I have a colleague, a very
accomplished neuroscientist,

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:02.830
who likes to take naps just after lunch,

01:03:02.830 --> 01:03:06.130
I personally like to take a
nap around 3:00 or 4:00 p.m.,

01:03:06.130 --> 01:03:07.390
but there's a practice

01:03:07.390 --> 01:03:09.820
that I've adopted in the last 5 years

01:03:09.820 --> 01:03:12.370
that I've found to be immensely beneficial

01:03:12.370 --> 01:03:15.340
that is sort of like
napping but isn't napping,

01:03:15.340 --> 01:03:18.740
it's a thing that they call yoga nidra,

01:03:18.740 --> 01:03:21.010
yoga nidra actually means yoga sleep,

01:03:21.010 --> 01:03:23.800
and it's a sort of meditation
that you listen to,

01:03:23.800 --> 01:03:24.810
there are number of scripts,

01:03:24.810 --> 01:03:26.450
I've talked about this on podcasts before

01:03:26.450 --> 01:03:29.710
but I'm going to post a link
to the two that I like most,

01:03:29.710 --> 01:03:33.620
that allows you to consciously

01:03:33.620 --> 01:03:36.290
bring your entire body and mind

01:03:36.290 --> 01:03:38.140
into a state of deep relaxation,

01:03:38.140 --> 01:03:41.210
and sometimes you fall asleep
and sometimes you don't,

01:03:41.210 --> 01:03:46.160
this is done for 10 to 30 or
even 60 minutes at a time.

01:03:46.160 --> 01:03:49.280
The other thing that works
really well is meditation,

01:03:49.280 --> 01:03:51.150
so I'm talking about naps,

01:03:51.150 --> 01:03:52.700
but I'm also talking about yoga nidra,

01:03:52.700 --> 01:03:54.510
which is sort of a form of meditation,

01:03:54.510 --> 01:03:57.490
and then more standard
forms of meditation,

01:03:57.490 --> 01:04:00.170
all three of those do something powerful

01:04:00.170 --> 01:04:02.240
which is that they bring our mind

01:04:02.240 --> 01:04:04.060
into a state of less so-called

01:04:04.060 --> 01:04:06.030
sympathetic nervous system activation,

01:04:06.030 --> 01:04:07.720
go back and listen to episode one

01:04:07.720 --> 01:04:08.880
if that doesn't make any sense,

01:04:08.880 --> 01:04:10.620
which is what governs your alertness,

01:04:10.620 --> 01:04:14.480
and instead, it activates
cells and circuits in your body

01:04:14.480 --> 01:04:16.970
that promote the
parasympathetic nervous system,

01:04:16.970 --> 01:04:18.710
or the calming system.

01:04:18.710 --> 01:04:20.920
A lot of people are
not good falling asleep

01:04:20.920 --> 01:04:23.830
because they're not good at calming down,

01:04:23.830 --> 01:04:26.200
so some people have no
trouble falling asleep,

01:04:26.200 --> 01:04:28.620
but many people have a
hard time falling asleep,

01:04:28.620 --> 01:04:30.310
or at least every once in a while

01:04:30.310 --> 01:04:32.310
experience challenges falling asleep.

01:04:32.310 --> 01:04:35.080
I don't have problems
falling asleep most nights,

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:37.130
but I've noticed that
if I'm working very hard

01:04:37.130 --> 01:04:39.040
or if the world is particularly stressful,

01:04:39.040 --> 01:04:41.410
my mind gets into a bit
of a kind of OCD loop

01:04:41.410 --> 01:04:42.850
where I tend to ruminate on things,

01:04:42.850 --> 01:04:44.513
and I'm not even thinking
about anything in particular,

01:04:44.513 --> 01:04:48.240
it's just challenging for me
to disengage and fall asleep.

01:04:48.240 --> 01:04:50.630
Meditation and yoga nidra scripts

01:04:50.630 --> 01:04:52.580
have been immensely helpful for me

01:04:52.580 --> 01:04:55.920
in terms of accelerating
the transition to sleep,

01:04:55.920 --> 01:04:58.770
so they involve taking a few minutes,

01:04:58.770 --> 01:05:00.070
10 to 30 minutes or so,

01:05:00.070 --> 01:05:01.510
just like you would for a nap,

01:05:01.510 --> 01:05:04.540
and just listening to a
script, almost passively,

01:05:04.540 --> 01:05:07.730
and it has you do some
particular patterns of breathing

01:05:07.730 --> 01:05:10.620
and some other kind of
body-scan-like things

01:05:10.620 --> 01:05:13.150
that can really help
people learn to relax,

01:05:13.150 --> 01:05:14.680
not just in that moment,

01:05:14.680 --> 01:05:17.520
but get better at relaxing
and turning off thinking

01:05:17.520 --> 01:05:20.720
in order to fall asleep when
they wanna do that at night.

01:05:20.720 --> 01:05:22.360
There's another thing
that's similar to this,

01:05:22.360 --> 01:05:25.040
which is certain forms
of hypnosis for sleep,

01:05:25.040 --> 01:05:26.870
for that, I'll just
refer you to the website

01:05:26.870 --> 01:05:28.960
of a colleague and collaborator of mine,

01:05:28.960 --> 01:05:32.270
David Spiegel, who's our associate chair

01:05:32.270 --> 01:05:35.580
of Psychiatry and Behavioral
Sciences at Stanford,

01:05:35.580 --> 01:05:37.150
he's developed a website,

01:05:37.150 --> 01:05:41.870
which is reverie,
R-E-V-E-R-I-E, health.com,

01:05:41.870 --> 01:05:43.620
so reveriehealth.com,

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:46.310
that has a lot of science-supported,

01:05:46.310 --> 01:05:49.380
clinically supported hypnosis scripts

01:05:49.380 --> 01:05:50.730
that essentially take the brain

01:05:50.730 --> 01:05:53.150
into states of deep relaxation

01:05:53.150 --> 01:05:55.870
for the sake of rewiring the
brain and neuroplasticity,

01:05:55.870 --> 01:05:57.430
but one of those scripts that's there

01:05:57.430 --> 01:05:59.930
and is available free is for sleep,

01:05:59.930 --> 01:06:01.970
and we'll talk more about
hypnosis at a later time

01:06:01.970 --> 01:06:04.320
because it has a ton of other effects

01:06:04.320 --> 01:06:06.223
that aren't just limited to sleep.

01:06:07.160 --> 01:06:09.370
So a period of time each day

01:06:09.370 --> 01:06:10.990
that you devote to getting better

01:06:10.990 --> 01:06:12.450
at falling and staying asleep

01:06:12.450 --> 01:06:15.130
is actually a really
good practice to adopt.

01:06:15.130 --> 01:06:16.600
The other thing about these practices

01:06:16.600 --> 01:06:19.800
like meditation, yoga nidra, and hypnosis,

01:06:19.800 --> 01:06:21.167
is people would always say to me,

01:06:21.167 --> 01:06:22.210
"Well, when should I do them?"

01:06:22.210 --> 01:06:24.077
and I always say, "Well, the
best time of day to do it

01:06:24.077 --> 01:06:26.027
"is when you first wake up in the morning,

01:06:26.027 --> 01:06:28.407
"provided you've gotten
your sunlight already,

01:06:28.407 --> 01:06:30.017
"anytime you wake up in
the middle of the night,

01:06:30.017 --> 01:06:30.960
"or any time of day."

01:06:30.960 --> 01:06:32.890
In other words, they're
always good for you

01:06:32.890 --> 01:06:34.510
because it's a training mechanism

01:06:34.510 --> 01:06:36.770
by which you self-train
your nervous system

01:06:36.770 --> 01:06:39.310
to go from a state of heightened alertness

01:06:39.310 --> 01:06:40.270
that you don't want

01:06:40.270 --> 01:06:43.450
to heightened relaxation that you do want,

01:06:43.450 --> 01:06:46.330
and so it's really teaching
you to hit the brake,

01:06:46.330 --> 01:06:48.990
and that brings us to an even
more important point, perhaps,

01:06:48.990 --> 01:06:51.550
which is, we've all experienced

01:06:51.550 --> 01:06:54.420
that we can stay up if we want to, right?

01:06:54.420 --> 01:06:56.920
If we wanna stay up late on New Year's

01:06:56.920 --> 01:06:58.280
or we wanna push an all-nighter,

01:06:58.280 --> 01:07:00.830
some people can do that
more easily than others,

01:07:00.830 --> 01:07:03.380
but we're all capable of doing that,

01:07:03.380 --> 01:07:05.900
but it's very hard to make
ourselves fall asleep,

01:07:05.900 --> 01:07:07.720
and so there's a sort of asymmetry

01:07:07.720 --> 01:07:09.660
to the way our autonomic nervous system,

01:07:09.660 --> 01:07:11.860
which governs this
alertness-calmness thing,

01:07:11.860 --> 01:07:14.350
the sympathetic and
parasympathetic nervous system,

01:07:14.350 --> 01:07:15.610
there's an asymmetry there

01:07:15.610 --> 01:07:19.500
where we are more easily
able to engage wakefulness

01:07:19.500 --> 01:07:20.520
and drive wakefulness,

01:07:20.520 --> 01:07:22.710
we can force ourselves to stay awake,

01:07:22.710 --> 01:07:26.370
than we are able to force
ourselves to fall asleep,

01:07:26.370 --> 01:07:29.350
and one of the things that
I say over and over again,

01:07:29.350 --> 01:07:31.520
and I'm gonna continue to
say over and over again,

01:07:31.520 --> 01:07:34.480
is it's very hard to control
the mind with the mind,

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:36.300
when you have trouble falling asleep,

01:07:36.300 --> 01:07:39.280
you need to look to some
mechanism that involves the body,

01:07:39.280 --> 01:07:40.670
and all the things I described,

01:07:40.670 --> 01:07:43.490
meditation, hypnosis, yoga nidra,

01:07:43.490 --> 01:07:46.760
all involve exhale-emphasized breathing,

01:07:46.760 --> 01:07:49.780
certain ways of lying down
and controlling the body,

01:07:49.780 --> 01:07:52.060
we're gonna get into
breathing in real depth

01:07:52.060 --> 01:07:53.110
at another time,

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:56.620
but all of those involve using
the body to control the mind

01:07:56.620 --> 01:07:58.960
rather than trying to, you know,

01:07:58.960 --> 01:08:02.640
wrestle your mind into a
certain pattern of relaxation,

01:08:02.640 --> 01:08:07.640
so earlier in episode one, I
talked about the Mobius strip,

01:08:07.860 --> 01:08:11.240
this continuous loop that is
the brain-body relationship,

01:08:11.240 --> 01:08:13.050
or the mind-body relationship,

01:08:13.050 --> 01:08:15.150
and when we're having
trouble controlling the mind,

01:08:15.150 --> 01:08:17.660
I encourage people to
look towards the body,

01:08:17.660 --> 01:08:19.020
look toward sunlight,

01:08:19.020 --> 01:08:20.760
avoid sunlight and bright light

01:08:20.760 --> 01:08:22.620
if that happens to be late at night,

01:08:22.620 --> 01:08:24.800
so there's a theme
that's starting to emerge

01:08:24.800 --> 01:08:26.170
which is, in order to control this thing

01:08:26.170 --> 01:08:27.550
that we call the nervous system,

01:08:27.550 --> 01:08:29.000
we have to look back to

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:30.660
some of the things we discussed earlier,

01:08:30.660 --> 01:08:33.000
like sensation, perception, et cetera,

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:35.170
but we have to ask, what can we control?

01:08:35.170 --> 01:08:37.800
Well, I'm talking about
controlling light exposure,

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:40.040
controlling your breathing and body,

01:08:40.040 --> 01:08:41.500
I'm not going into details right now

01:08:41.500 --> 01:08:43.170
but you can see the yoga nidra script

01:08:43.170 --> 01:08:45.200
or the reveriehealth.com,

01:08:45.200 --> 01:08:46.930
or Headspace would be a great place

01:08:46.930 --> 01:08:49.440
to adopt a meditation practice,

01:08:49.440 --> 01:08:51.050
any of those are really teaching you

01:08:51.050 --> 01:08:53.320
to use your body to control your mind,

01:08:53.320 --> 01:08:56.210
and to allow you to explore
the mind-body relationship

01:08:56.210 --> 01:08:58.480
in a way that gives you more control

01:08:58.480 --> 01:09:02.360
over your mind and the
mind-body relationship, okay?

01:09:02.360 --> 01:09:04.650
So we talked about light,

01:09:04.650 --> 01:09:06.980
we talked about activity
and timing of light,

01:09:06.980 --> 01:09:09.200
we talked about the usefulness of naps,

01:09:09.200 --> 01:09:12.420
and these things that I'm
calling non-sleep deep rest,

01:09:12.420 --> 01:09:16.880
which include meditation,
yoga nidra, and hypnosis,

01:09:16.880 --> 01:09:18.680
non-sleep deep rest,

01:09:18.680 --> 01:09:23.170
or what I, hereafter, we
will refer to as NSDR,

01:09:23.170 --> 01:09:25.010
not to be confused with EMDR,

01:09:25.010 --> 01:09:26.730
I don't think I've ever heard NSDR,

01:09:26.730 --> 01:09:31.730
so I'm planting a flag for
NSDR, non-sleep deep rest,

01:09:32.080 --> 01:09:36.330
as a way to reset one's
ability to be awake

01:09:36.330 --> 01:09:38.130
after you emerge from NSDR,

01:09:38.130 --> 01:09:40.620
so to get some more wakefulness
and ability to attend,

01:09:40.620 --> 01:09:43.560
some emotional stability, reset,

01:09:43.560 --> 01:09:47.680
as well as make it better
and easier to fall asleep

01:09:47.680 --> 01:09:49.490
when you wanna go to sleep at night.

01:09:49.490 --> 01:09:51.030
Now, the non-sleep deep rest

01:09:51.030 --> 01:09:53.180
does have some research to support it,

01:09:53.180 --> 01:09:54.970
there's a beautiful study done

01:09:54.970 --> 01:09:56.970
out of a university in Denmark,

01:09:56.970 --> 01:09:59.700
I will later provide a link to that study,

01:09:59.700 --> 01:10:02.410
that showed that this meditation

01:10:02.410 --> 01:10:05.250
and yoga nidra-type meditation

01:10:05.250 --> 01:10:08.140
allows dopamine and other neuromodulators

01:10:08.140 --> 01:10:09.790
in an area of the brain
called the striatum

01:10:09.790 --> 01:10:13.040
that's involved in motor
planning and motor execution,

01:10:13.040 --> 01:10:14.410
to reset itself,

01:10:14.410 --> 01:10:17.890
in other words, this NSDR
can reset our ability

01:10:17.890 --> 01:10:21.580
to engage in the world in a
way that's very deliberate,

01:10:21.580 --> 01:10:22.990
and not to throw in another acronym,

01:10:22.990 --> 01:10:26.240
but NSDR resets your
ability to engage in DPOs,

01:10:26.240 --> 01:10:27.850
duration, path, and outcome,

01:10:27.850 --> 01:10:29.397
so now you're probably
rolling your eyes like,

01:10:29.397 --> 01:10:30.940
"Oh my goodness, the number of acronyms,"

01:10:30.940 --> 01:10:35.940
but just bear with me
because NSDR is so powerful,

01:10:36.170 --> 01:10:39.290
because first of all, it doesn't require

01:10:39.290 --> 01:10:41.380
that you rig yourself to any device,

01:10:41.380 --> 01:10:44.450
it doesn't require that you
take much time out of your day,

01:10:44.450 --> 01:10:47.830
it doesn't require that you
ingest anything, except air,

01:10:47.830 --> 01:10:51.280
and it can have so many positive effects

01:10:51.280 --> 01:10:53.450
right down to the neuromodulator level,

01:10:53.450 --> 01:10:54.910
so I think in the years to come,

01:10:54.910 --> 01:10:56.270
my lab's exploring this

01:10:56.270 --> 01:10:58.460
in a collaboration with
David Spiegel's lab,

01:10:58.460 --> 01:10:59.713
but other labs are
looking at this as well,

01:10:59.713 --> 01:11:04.080
I think NSDR is going to start
to play a more prominent role

01:11:04.080 --> 01:11:06.150
in what we call wellness and health,

01:11:06.150 --> 01:11:07.570
both mental health and physical health,

01:11:07.570 --> 01:11:09.960
so I encourage you to
explore those practices.

01:11:09.960 --> 01:11:12.410
Okay, so what about things that we can

01:11:12.410 --> 01:11:14.370
and maybe should or should not take

01:11:14.370 --> 01:11:17.640
in order to control
and access better sleep

01:11:17.640 --> 01:11:18.900
and better wakefulness?

01:11:18.900 --> 01:11:22.870
We've talked about things
you can do or not do,

01:11:22.870 --> 01:11:26.290
we've talked about nutrition
and the timing of nutrition,

01:11:26.290 --> 01:11:27.700
now let's talk about compounds,

01:11:27.700 --> 01:11:29.130
those could be prescription drugs,

01:11:29.130 --> 01:11:30.860
those could be supplements,

01:11:30.860 --> 01:11:31.920
there are a number of different things

01:11:31.920 --> 01:11:36.100
that will affect your
circadian timing and behavior,

01:11:36.100 --> 01:11:40.480
in fact, almost everything
that you could take

01:11:41.410 --> 01:11:44.060
will affect your circadian
timing and behavior,

01:11:44.060 --> 01:11:44.893
that's right.

01:11:44.893 --> 01:11:47.510
So years ago when I
was in graduate school,

01:11:47.510 --> 01:11:49.490
I had a professor, unfortunately,
he passed away now,

01:11:49.490 --> 01:11:52.170
but his name was Ted Jones,
the late Edward Jones,

01:11:52.170 --> 01:11:53.940
who was a world-class neuroanatomist,

01:11:53.940 --> 01:11:55.170
he wrote the book on the thalamus,

01:11:55.170 --> 01:11:57.640
in fact, it's called "The Thalamus,"

01:11:57.640 --> 01:12:00.470
and an expert on patterns
of activation in the brain

01:12:00.470 --> 01:12:01.520
during sleep,

01:12:01.520 --> 01:12:04.020
and I'll never forget that
during one of these lectures,

01:12:04.020 --> 01:12:06.237
someone asked Ted the question,

01:12:06.237 --> 01:12:08.247
"What is the effect of some drug

01:12:08.247 --> 01:12:11.340
"on these waves of activity in
the thalamus?" or something,

01:12:11.340 --> 01:12:13.430
and his answer was incredible.

01:12:13.430 --> 01:12:15.440
Now, he was a pretty gruff guy,

01:12:15.440 --> 01:12:17.230
and so his answer was delivered

01:12:17.230 --> 01:12:19.510
in the form of a kind of
aggressive direct statement,

01:12:19.510 --> 01:12:22.407
he said, "A drug is a substance

01:12:22.407 --> 01:12:24.407
"that when injected into a person,

01:12:24.407 --> 01:12:26.960
"produces a scientific publication,"

01:12:26.960 --> 01:12:29.840
and what he was saying
is actually quite true,

01:12:29.840 --> 01:12:32.890
which is that most every compound

01:12:32.890 --> 01:12:36.210
will have some effect on
some aspect of biology,

01:12:36.210 --> 01:12:37.043
this is why it's hard

01:12:37.043 --> 01:12:38.640
to sort through everything
that's on PubMed,

01:12:38.640 --> 01:12:43.550
if you put any molecule or
compound or drug into PubMed

01:12:43.550 --> 01:12:47.160
and then you put sleep next to
it, or alertness next to it,

01:12:47.160 --> 01:12:49.940
you're likely to find a paper
where there's an effect,

01:12:49.940 --> 01:12:53.410
but that's not necessarily telling you

01:12:53.410 --> 01:12:55.850
that that drug is helpful for that,

01:12:55.850 --> 01:12:56.870
what it's telling you is

01:12:56.870 --> 01:13:00.560
that anytime you change what you take

01:13:00.560 --> 01:13:02.740
or you stop taking something,

01:13:02.740 --> 01:13:05.270
say you're taking sleeping
pills, Ambien or whatever it is,

01:13:05.270 --> 01:13:06.250
and you stop taking them,

01:13:06.250 --> 01:13:08.780
your sleep behavior will change.

01:13:08.780 --> 01:13:09.707
Let's stay you take an aspirin

01:13:09.707 --> 01:13:11.160
and you don't normally take aspirin,

01:13:11.160 --> 01:13:13.320
you will shift your circadian rhythm,

01:13:13.320 --> 01:13:15.240
now you might not shift it perceptibly,

01:13:15.240 --> 01:13:17.140
you might not create
problems for yourself,

01:13:17.140 --> 01:13:20.850
but anytime you ingest a
compound at high potency,

01:13:20.850 --> 01:13:24.140
you're going to provide some
shift to your circadian rhythm.

01:13:24.140 --> 01:13:26.020
Now, that said, there are a couple things

01:13:26.020 --> 01:13:28.240
that are directly in line with the biology

01:13:28.240 --> 01:13:29.950
related to falling and staying asleep

01:13:29.950 --> 01:13:32.950
and directly in line with
the biology of wakefulness,

01:13:32.950 --> 01:13:34.790
there's a whole category of things,

01:13:34.790 --> 01:13:37.800
like stimulants, cocaine, amphetamine,

01:13:37.800 --> 01:13:40.640
and prescription stimulants, that are,

01:13:40.640 --> 01:13:42.100
the prescription ones were designed

01:13:42.100 --> 01:13:43.490
for the treatment of narcolepsy,

01:13:43.490 --> 01:13:46.770
so things like modafinil or armodafinil

01:13:46.770 --> 01:13:48.180
that are designed to created wakefulness,

01:13:48.180 --> 01:13:52.710
they are all essentially chemical variants

01:13:52.710 --> 01:13:55.630
of things that increase
epinephrine and dopamine.

01:13:55.630 --> 01:13:58.130
Now, of course, I'm of the standpoint

01:13:58.130 --> 01:13:59.650
that things like cocaine and amphetamine

01:13:59.650 --> 01:14:01.180
are just across the board bad,

01:14:01.180 --> 01:14:04.090
they have so many addictive
and terrible effects,

01:14:04.090 --> 01:14:08.100
in the proper setting prescribed
by the proper professional,

01:14:08.100 --> 01:14:12.340
things like modafinil for
narcolepsy might be appropriate,

01:14:12.340 --> 01:14:15.610
I know that a lot of people
out there take Adderall,

01:14:15.610 --> 01:14:18.100
even though they haven't
been prescribed Adderall,

01:14:18.100 --> 01:14:20.410
in order to increase wakefulness,

01:14:20.410 --> 01:14:24.060
that is essentially, well,
it's illegal for one,

01:14:24.060 --> 01:14:26.150
but also it's abusing the system

01:14:26.150 --> 01:14:27.530
in the sense that you're pushing back

01:14:27.530 --> 01:14:29.470
on the adenosine system
slightly differently

01:14:29.470 --> 01:14:31.140
than you do caffeine,

01:14:31.140 --> 01:14:32.370
it will make you feel more alert,

01:14:32.370 --> 01:14:33.600
there tends to be a heavy rebound

01:14:33.600 --> 01:14:35.370
and they do have an addictive potential,

01:14:35.370 --> 01:14:36.950
there are also some other effects of those

01:14:36.950 --> 01:14:37.783
that could be quite bad,

01:14:37.783 --> 01:14:40.070
so we're gonna explore stimulants

01:14:40.070 --> 01:14:42.870
in a whole month related to drugs,

01:14:42.870 --> 01:14:44.270
but there are some supplements

01:14:44.270 --> 01:14:48.330
and some things that are
safer, certainly safer,

01:14:48.330 --> 01:14:50.920
and that, in cases where you're

01:14:50.920 --> 01:14:52.250
doing all the right behaviors,

01:14:52.250 --> 01:14:54.770
you're exercising and eating correctly

01:14:54.770 --> 01:14:56.470
and you're still having
trouble with sleep,

01:14:56.470 --> 01:15:00.070
that can be beneficial for
falling and staying asleep.

01:15:00.070 --> 01:15:02.570
Now, I wanna be very clear,
I am not pushing supplements,

01:15:02.570 --> 01:15:04.800
I am just pointing you toward some things

01:15:04.800 --> 01:15:07.370
that have been shown in
peer-reviewed studies

01:15:07.370 --> 01:15:08.420
to have some benefit.

01:15:09.490 --> 01:15:11.870
The first one is magnesium,

01:15:11.870 --> 01:15:13.390
there are many forms of magnesium,

01:15:13.390 --> 01:15:14.770
but certain forms of magnesium

01:15:14.770 --> 01:15:17.610
can have positive effects on sleepiness

01:15:17.610 --> 01:15:18.900
and the ability to stay asleep,

01:15:18.900 --> 01:15:23.660
mainly by way of increasing
neurotransmitters like GABA

01:15:23.660 --> 01:15:26.820
which help turn off the DPO,

01:15:26.820 --> 01:15:28.290
the kind of thinking about the future,

01:15:28.290 --> 01:15:29.910
duration-path-outcome analysis,

01:15:29.910 --> 01:15:34.910
and make one's mind kind
of drift in space and time

01:15:35.040 --> 01:15:36.740
and make it easier to fall asleep,

01:15:36.740 --> 01:15:38.520
there are a lot of forms
of magnesium out there,

01:15:38.520 --> 01:15:43.520
but in particular is magnesium
threonate, T-H-R-E-O-N-A-T-E,

01:15:44.030 --> 01:15:47.320
which you have to check to
see if this is right for you,

01:15:47.320 --> 01:15:48.460
check with your doctor,

01:15:48.460 --> 01:15:50.010
but magnesium threonate is

01:15:50.010 --> 01:15:52.390
associated with transporters in the body

01:15:52.390 --> 01:15:54.530
that bring more of it into cells

01:15:54.530 --> 01:15:57.370
that allow people to feel
this kind of drowsiness

01:15:57.370 --> 01:15:58.420
and help them fall asleep,

01:15:58.420 --> 01:16:01.140
so I personally, I can only
talk about what I personally do,

01:16:01.140 --> 01:16:04.870
I personally take 3 or 400
milligrams of magnesium threonate

01:16:04.870 --> 01:16:07.420
about 30 to 60 minutes before sleep,

01:16:07.420 --> 01:16:08.870
and it helps me fall asleep.

01:16:08.870 --> 01:16:13.370
The other thing is theanine, T-H-E-A,

01:16:13.370 --> 01:16:17.792
T-H-E-A-N-I-N-E, theanine,

01:16:17.792 --> 01:16:20.160
100 to 200 milligrams of theanine, for me,

01:16:20.160 --> 01:16:23.000
also helps me turn off
my mind and fall asleep,

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:24.980
I take it 30 to 60 minutes
throughout the day.

01:16:24.980 --> 01:16:27.380
Interestingly, theanine
is now being introduced

01:16:27.380 --> 01:16:29.350
to a lot of energy drinks

01:16:29.350 --> 01:16:31.560
in order to take away the jitters

01:16:31.560 --> 01:16:33.940
that are associated with
drinking too much caffeine

01:16:33.940 --> 01:16:36.150
or with some other things
that are in the energy drinks,

01:16:36.150 --> 01:16:39.160
energy drinks can be problematic,

01:16:39.160 --> 01:16:41.830
they can contain a lot of L-taurine,

01:16:41.830 --> 01:16:42.820
I'll just tell you an anecdote,

01:16:42.820 --> 01:16:43.653
when I was a postdoc,

01:16:43.653 --> 01:16:45.670
I was drinking a lot of a
particular energy drink,

01:16:45.670 --> 01:16:47.870
it has a lot of taurine in it,

01:16:47.870 --> 01:16:51.130
and actually the whites of my eyes,

01:16:51.130 --> 01:16:52.210
the sclera, as it's called,

01:16:52.210 --> 01:16:54.480
of my eyes turned beet red,

01:16:54.480 --> 01:16:57.710
and I went to a friend
who's an ophthalmologist,

01:16:57.710 --> 01:16:59.727
I said, "Look, I'm not a marijuana smoker,

01:16:59.727 --> 01:17:00.847
"I haven't been hit on the head,

01:17:00.847 --> 01:17:02.070
"I don't know what's going on,"

01:17:02.070 --> 01:17:03.017
and he looked and he said,

01:17:03.017 --> 01:17:06.420
"I think you've got some
microvascular damage,"

01:17:06.420 --> 01:17:08.440
and we walked through what
I was taking and doing,

01:17:08.440 --> 01:17:10.387
and he said, "Oh, it's
probably the taurine,

01:17:10.387 --> 01:17:11.527
"excessive levels of taurine

01:17:11.527 --> 01:17:13.930
"can create some microvascular damage."

01:17:13.930 --> 01:17:15.960
So if you're having
microvascular damage in your eye,

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:17.440
you probably have microvascular damage

01:17:17.440 --> 01:17:19.770
deeper in your skull, so I stopped,

01:17:19.770 --> 01:17:21.760
that's the reason why I
don't take energy drinks,

01:17:21.760 --> 01:17:23.990
so just a consideration,

01:17:23.990 --> 01:17:25.940
again, I'm not here to tell
you what to do or not do,

01:17:25.940 --> 01:17:28.143
but just wanna arm you with information.

01:17:31.067 --> 01:17:33.030
The thing about theanine and magnesium

01:17:33.030 --> 01:17:35.440
is taken together, they
do, for some people,

01:17:35.440 --> 01:17:38.240
they can make them so
sleepy and sleep so deeply

01:17:38.240 --> 01:17:40.010
that they actually have trouble
waking up in the morning,

01:17:40.010 --> 01:17:42.170
so you have to play with
these things and titrate them

01:17:42.170 --> 01:17:43.270
if you decide to use them,

01:17:43.270 --> 01:17:44.830
again, if you decide to go this route,

01:17:44.830 --> 01:17:47.110
I would not start by taking supplements,

01:17:47.110 --> 01:17:48.120
I would start by getting your

01:17:48.120 --> 01:17:50.470
light-viewing behavior correct,

01:17:50.470 --> 01:17:52.030
and then think about your nutrition

01:17:52.030 --> 01:17:53.330
and then think about your activity

01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:55.800
and then think about whether
or not you wanna supplement,

01:17:55.800 --> 01:17:57.900
we already talked about melatonin earlier.

01:17:57.900 --> 01:17:59.860
There's another supplement
that could be quite useful,

01:17:59.860 --> 01:18:03.740
which is apigenin, A-P-I-G-E-N-I-N,

01:18:03.740 --> 01:18:05.710
which is a derivative of chamomile,

01:18:05.710 --> 01:18:10.050
50 milligrams of apigenin
also can augment or support

01:18:10.050 --> 01:18:13.200
this kind of creation of a sleepiness

01:18:13.200 --> 01:18:15.440
to help fall asleep and stay asleep.

01:18:15.440 --> 01:18:19.160
A note about sleepwalkers and
people with very vivid dreams,

01:18:19.160 --> 01:18:21.740
theanine can often make
your dreams very vivid,

01:18:21.740 --> 01:18:24.460
sleepwalkers should be
careful about taking theanine,

01:18:24.460 --> 01:18:26.840
everyone should be careful
about taking anything,

01:18:26.840 --> 01:18:27.830
and don't take anything

01:18:27.830 --> 01:18:30.240
without consulting your
board-certified M.D.

01:18:30.240 --> 01:18:33.150
or healthcare professional first, okay?

01:18:33.150 --> 01:18:34.760
Your health is your responsibility,

01:18:34.760 --> 01:18:36.140
I am not gonna take responsibility

01:18:36.140 --> 01:18:38.780
for what you decide to do
experimentally in any case,

01:18:38.780 --> 01:18:41.680
but especially as it relates
to supplementation and drugs.

01:18:43.660 --> 01:18:45.900
As a important point, apigenin

01:18:45.900 --> 01:18:48.600
is a fairly potent estrogen inhibitor,

01:18:48.600 --> 01:18:52.320
so women who want to keep
their estrogen levels high,

01:18:52.320 --> 01:18:54.270
or at whatever levels
they happen to be at,

01:18:54.270 --> 01:18:56.760
should probably avoid apigenin altogether,

01:18:56.760 --> 01:19:00.360
and men, take that into
consideration as well,

01:19:00.360 --> 01:19:01.620
men need estrogen also,

01:19:01.620 --> 01:19:03.980
you don't wanna completely
eliminate your estrogen,

01:19:03.980 --> 01:19:05.680
that it can create all
sorts of bad effects

01:19:05.680 --> 01:19:08.270
on libido and cognition, et cetera,

01:19:08.270 --> 01:19:10.290
so apigenin in some people

01:19:10.290 --> 01:19:12.120
is gonna be a pretty
strong estrogen inhibitor,

01:19:12.120 --> 01:19:13.663
so keep that in mind.

01:19:14.630 --> 01:19:15.870
There are other things you can take

01:19:15.870 --> 01:19:17.500
to help you sleep better,

01:19:17.500 --> 01:19:20.260
those are the legal ones
that, at least I'm aware of,

